revision.text:
[[Image:Porters.PNG|right|thumb|250px|Comparison of active transport proteins]] [[Image:antiporter.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Antiporter illustration]] An '''antiporter''' (also called '''exchanger''' or '''counter-transporter''') is a [[cotransporter]] and [[integral membrane protein]] involved in [[secondary active transport]] of two or more different molecules or ions across a [[phospholipid membrane]] such as the [[plasma membrane]] in opposite directions. [[Sodium-proton antiporter|Na<sup>+</sup>/H<sup>+</sup> antiporter]]s have been reviewed.<ref name="EtanaMeytal">{{cite book|first1= Etana |last1= Padan |first2= Meytal |last2= Landau |publisher= Springer |publication-date= 2016|series= Metal Ions in Life Sciences |volume=16 |title= The Alkali Metal Ions: Their Role in Life |editor1-last=Astrid |editor1-first= Sigel |editor2-last=Helmut|editor2-first=Sigel |editor3-last=Roland K.O. |editor3-first= Sigel |chapter= Chapter 12. Sodium-Proton (Na<sup>+</sup>/H<sup>+</sup>) Antiporters: Properties and Roles in Health and Disease |pages= 391–458 |doi=10.1007/978-3-319-21756-7_12 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cYuRCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA391}}</ref>
In [[secondary active transport]], one species of solute moves along its [[electrochemical gradient]], allowing a different species to move against its own electrochemical gradient. This movement is in contrast to [[primary active transport]], in which all solutes are moved against their [[concentration gradient]]s, fueled by [[Adenosine triphosphate|ATP]].
Transport may involve one or more of each type of solute. For example, the [[Sodium-calcium exchanger|Na<sup>+</sup>/Ca<sup>2+</sup> exchanger]], used by many cells to remove cytoplasmic calcium, exchanges one calcium ion for three sodium ions.
